In following snippet, the call to `$this->analyse->someClass($class);` leads to an error due to `$class` being inferred as `mixed`.

I'm not sure if that's due to `class_exists()` (leading to `!class-string` type inference, which is very likely expected) or due to `class-string<ClassType>` parameter not having a concrete declaration.

```php
<?php

/**
 * @psalm-template ClassType
 */
class AnalyseSomeStuff
{
    /**
     * @psalm-param class-string<ClassType> $theClass
     */
    public function someClass(string $theClass) : void
    {
        echo $theClass;
    }
}

class MyAutoloader
{
    /** @var AnalyseSomeStuff */
    private $analyse;

    public function __construct(AnalyseSomeStuff $analyse)
    {
        $this->analyse = $analyse;
    }

    /**
     * @psalm-param class-string $class
     *
     * @psalm-suppress RedundantConditionGivenDocblockType - autoloaders do need to check class existence
     */
    public function autoload(string $class) : bool
    {
        if (class_exists($class, false)) {
            return false;
        }

        $this->analyse->someClass($class);

        return true;
    }
}
```

